<b>New Design!</b><p>MarkupValidator has a new look!</p><p>We've been working on a new interface that we hope will make our tool easier for everyone. Have you checked it out?</p><p><img width="350" alt="new design" src="http://sitevalidator.com/images/news_5_1.jpg"></p><b>MarkupValidator Accounts</b><p>Now you can create a user account on MarkupValidator using your email and password, in case you prefer this to signing with your Twitter, Google or Facebook account.</p><p><img width="350" alt="new login page" src="http://sitevalidator.com/images/news_5_2.png"></p><p>If you have already an account using one of those external services you don't need to do anything and can continue logging in as usual, but you can easily migrate to email+password from 'My Account'.</p><p><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="https://www.w3clove.com/account">https://www.w3clove.com/account</a></p><b>HTTPS Everywhere!</b><p>Security is important!</p><p>Now all the app uses HTTPS, so all communication between you and our server is encrypted. No need to configure anything on your side.</p><b>Dedicated Validation Server</b><p>We want to provide the best response times to our users so, to avoid timeouts, we've set up our own, dedicated validation server, for internal use only.</p><p>So now when you validate your sites on MarkupValidator, all validations happen in-house, we control the whole process.</p><b>Open Source Love</b><p>MarkupValidator wouldn't be possible without Open Source, and we give back to the Open Source community!</p><p>We've sponsored the making of this step-by-step guide about installing the W3C validator software on a dedicated server:&nbsp;<br><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="https://github.com/tlvince/w3c-validator-guide">https://github.com/tlvince/w3c-validator-guide</a></p><p>We've added multiple workers capability to this heroku scaling gem. It's what makes us being able to scale automatically our background jobs queue depending on the work load:&nbsp;<br><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="https://github.com/jaimeiniesta/workless/tree/multiple_workers">https://github.com/jaimeiniesta/workless/tree/multiple_workers</a></p><p>We've fixed bugs and improved the API on the metainspector gem. It's what we use to scrape your sites:&nbsp;<br><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="https://github.com/jaimeiniesta/metainspector">https://github.com/jaimeiniesta/metainspector</a></p><p>And last but not least, the open source version of MarkupValidator has been updated, too:&nbsp;<br><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="https://github.com/jaimeiniesta/w3clove">https://github.com/jaimeiniesta/w3clove</a></p><b>API Authentication</b><p>We've added authentication to the MarkupValidator API, so now you can identify yourself when making requests.</p><p>Check out the documentation:</p><p><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://developer.w3clove.com/api/authentication">http://developer.w3clove.com/api/authentication</a></p><b>Status Page</b><p>We've got a brand new status page!</p><p>And hey, we've got a 99.95% uptime (only interrupted when we deploy new features to the server)&nbsp;<br><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://status.w3clove.com/">http://status.w3clove.com</a></p><p>...and that's all for this month!&nbsp;<br>Have a nice summer, and see you in August!</p><p>Love and validations,&nbsp;<br>Jaime -- MarkupValidator</p>
